<section xml:id="sec-roots-of-quadratic-and-cubic-equations" original="PRECALC/modules/m49337/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Roots of Quadratic and Cubic Equations</title>

  <!-- Content summary: - Key focus is visualizing the solutions to equations by identifying where a curve meets the x-axis. - Illustrate plotting curves for y = ax^2 + bx + c and x = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d. - -->

  <objectives>
 Solve quadratic and cubic equations graphically
  </objectives>

  <!-- Add <insight> here -->

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from PRECALC fs-id1165135693703: Finding the x- and y-Intercepts of a Quadratic Function -->
  
  <p>Much as we did in the application problems above, we also need to find intercepts of quadratic equations for graphing parabolas. Recall that we find the <m>y\text{ - }</m> intercept of a quadratic by evaluating the function at an input of zero, and we find the <m>x\text{ - }</m> intercepts at locations where the output is zero. Notice in <xref ref="PRECALC-kybyAPSJGS"/> that the number of <m>x\text{ - }</m> intercepts can vary depending upon the location of the graph.</p>
  
  <figure xml:id="PRECALC-kybyAPSJGS" original="PRECALC/modules/m49337/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <caption>Number of <m>x</m>-intercepts of a parabola</caption>
      <image source="PRECALC/CNX_Precalc_Figure_03_02_013.jpg" width="80%"/>
    </figure>
  
  <insight xml:id="PRECALC-sL3p3ciWTK" original="PRECALC/modules/m49337/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>
        <em>Given a quadratic function <m>f(x),</m> find the <m>y\text{ - }</m> and <m>x</m>-intercepts.</em>
      </title>
      <ol>
        <li>Evaluate <m>f(0)</m> to find the <m>y\text{ - }</m> intercept.</li>
        <li>Solve the quadratic equation <m>f(x)=0</m> to find the <m>x</m>-intercepts.</li>
      </ol>
    </insight>
  
  <example xml:id="PRECALC-M7X7aLDPaJ" original="PRECALC/modules/m49337/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Finding the</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the <m>y</m>- and <m>x</m>-intercepts of the quadratic <m>f(x)=3x^{2}+5x-2.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>We find the <m>y</m>-intercept by evaluating <m>f(0).</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>f(0)=3(0)^{2}+5(0)-2</mrow>
            <mrow>=-2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>So the <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,−2).</m>
        </p>
        <p>For the <m>x</m>-intercepts, we find all solutions of <m>f(x)=0.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>0=3x^{2}+5x-2</me>
        </p>
        <p>In this case, the quadratic can be factored easily, providing the simplest method for solution.</p>
        <p>
          <me>0=(3x-1)(x+2)</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>0=3x-1 &amp; 0=x+2</mrow>
            <mrow>x=\frac{1}{3} &amp; \text{ or } &amp; x=-2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>So the <m>x</m>-intercepts are at <m>(\frac{1}{3},0)</m> and <m>(-2,0).</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-roots-of-quadratic-and-cubic-equations" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-college-algebra-bundle/tree/e10e6b91143fe884c7c60dc0ad82ef23e1be0aa5/modules/m49337/index.cnxml">Finding the x- and y-Intercepts of a Quadratic Function</url>" in Open STAX Precalculus 2e, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->
</section>
